{"answer":"To compute the Frobenius powers of the ideal (xy^2, x^3 + y^3) in k[x,y], you can start by defining the polynomial ring and the ideal in Macaulay2. The Frobenius powers of an ideal can be computed using the following code snippet:

```m2
R = QQ[x,y];
I = ideal(x*y^2, x^3 + y^3);
FrobeniusPower(I, n)
```

In this code:
- `R` defines the polynomial ring over the rational numbers.
- `I` is the ideal generated by the polynomials `xy^2` and `x^3 + y^3`.
- Replace `n` with the desired Frobenius power, for example, `1`, `2`, etc. The `FrobeniusPower` function computes the n-th Frobenius power of the ideal.","references":["[functions\ideal-doc.m2] convert a monomial ideal to an ideal","[functions\ideal-doc.m2] get the defining ideal","[functions\ideal-doc.m2] convert a module to an ideal"]}
